In such cases, you need to exchange some of the light pieces in order to
reduce the opponent's counterplay. Then, you need to attack this pawn with
your heavy pieces. Hence, White tries to exchange the knights, and then, to
increase the pressure against the c5-pawn.} (14. Bg5 $5) (14. Rfd1 $5) 14...
Qb6 15. Nxc6 Rxc6 16. b3 {Another very good and didactic move. White has other
ways to protect the b2-pawn; for example, to play Rc2. However, he uses the
economical defense (if you don't know what it is, you are welcome to study the
RCA course "Defending Champion") and, similarly, he is blocking the c4-square.
Moreover, he creates a solid outpost on a4 for the knight. From there, the
knight can free the c-line and increase the pressure against the c5-square.} h6
17. Rfd1 Qb7 (17... Qa6 $5 {It's not recommended to transpose the game into
the endgame when you have a pawn weakness, but here Black can hope for an
active counterplay with his pieces.} 18. Qxa6 Rxa6 19. Na4 Nd5 $132) 18. h3
Rfc8 19. Na4 $14 {You can see clearly White's strategy in action. He blocked
the c-pawn, his pieces are active and Black has the luck to counterplay. In
order to have a successful strategy against the isolated pawn, you need to
block or control the square, and then, to attack it with your pieces. Then you
have two strategies: Firstly, you can regroup your pieces in order to continue
pressing this pawn, by doubling the rooks on the c-line, and put the queen on
c1 behind the rooks. This is the Alekhine gun. Secondly, you need to find a
second weakness. You can continue activating your pieces; for example,
doubling the rooks on the d-line, and then, creating a kingside superiority,
by bringing there more pieces. In any case, Carlsen has a small but stable
advantage here, and he manages to win the game afterwards.} Nd7 20. Rd2 Nb6 21.
