Bxd4 Bb5 16. O-O Nf5 17. Bf2 h5 18. a4 Bxd3 19. cxd3 Rc8 20. a5 {Diagram #} d4
$1 {Black has a very active knight on f5 and he hasn't castle yet; thus, you
may think that it's possible to start a kingside attack. However, Black's
intention is to control the center, secure the knight outpost with h5 and play
a position with a good knight against a bad bishop. Black plays the best move
in the position, a5! He limits the mobility of the bishop, stops it from
landing on b6 and secures his dominance on the c-line. Black's main goal is to
fight for the initiative and activity of his pieces.} (20... h4 $5) (20... Qc6
$5) (20... Qe7 $2 21. Bc5 $5 (21. Rc2 $5)) (20... Qd7 $6 21. Bc5) 21. Ra1 Qd7 {
He is dominating on the light squares, overprotecting the important d4-pawn
and preparing to 0-0 and double the rooks on the c-line.} 22. Qf3 Qd5 {
It is totally ok for Black to exchange queens even if he doubles the central
pawns. White cannot attack them because it cannot enter the files. After the
queen's exchange, Black's king will be safe on d7, and Black's plan is to
double on the c-line. The rooks belong to the open lines. Please also notice
that the doubled pawns will help Black find a good outpost on the c-line in
order to use it and double the rooks there.} 23. Qxd5 exd5 24. Rfc1 Kd7 25. Be1
{This is another very cool move! White successfully cover the entry points on
the c-file, and Black cannot make any progress there easily. For that reason,
Black is trying to open more lines for the rooks. He is trying to open the g-
and e-lines. Probably, he will not be able to attack the king by doubling the
rooks on the g-line, but the e-file will be important. It will be difficult
for White to protect all of the entry squares.} f6 26. exf6 gxf6 27. Kf2 Ne3
