Ne7 9. b4 Ne8 {Diagram #} 10. c5 $5 {The King's Indian Defense (KID) is a
characteristic opening in which White makes a queenside attack and Black tries
to checkmate White's monarch. If Black's attack fails or delays, then he's
dead lost from the other side of the board. This is a critical moment for
White because he has plenty of moves available. White's main strategical idea
is to break through with the c5 move, which Ernst played immediately.} (10. a3
$5) (10. Bg5 $5 {The idea is to delay the kingside maneuvers.}) (10. a4 $5) (
10. b5 $6) (10. Re1 $5) (10. Qb3 $5) 10... f5 11. Nd2 {This is a typical
regrouping move that fights for e4 outpost, prepares the f3-advancement and
makes more solid the bone structure, and transfers the knight to the new free
c4-square.} Nf6 12. a4 f4 13. Nc4 {We can see clearly now how White is
improving his queenside attack by pressing the d6-pawn hardly. The computer
gives clearly the advantage to White and, indeed, he has a strategic advantage.
However, the attack against the enemy king is often very dangerous and, for
that, KID is very popular for playing at any level.} g5 14. Nb5 {White continues
pressing the same square, d6. This is a model game on how to attack with
White against the KID.} Ne8 15. Ba3 {Even if this bishop looks closed, it has
an eye on the d6-pawn. If you imagine that the d6-pawn is the opponent king,
then you can develop your attack against that square more naturally, am I
right?} Ng6 16. Bg4 {This is a very important strategic exchange because
Black's light-squared bishop is an important piece on the attack. White has
the advantage here because his attack is faster. After a long and fighting
game, he manages to win it afterwards.} Bxg4 17. Qxg4 Rf7 18. f3 Bf6 19. Rfd1
